Here's the pattern using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In `App.xaml.cs`** â€” override `CreateWindow` and use a custom Window subclass:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}

public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        // Save draft when app backgrounds
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        // Restore draft when app returns
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            note.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

1. **Use `OnStopped`** for save â€” it fires when the app is no longer visible (not `OnDeactivated`, which fires for dialogs/notification shade).
2. **Also save in `OnDestroying`** â€” on Android, the back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying`.
3. **Keep it fast** â€” `Preferences` is ideal for small strings. Avoid database writes here (Android has a ~5s ANR timeout).
4. **`OnResumed` doesn't fire on first launch** â€” the initial sequence is `Created` â†’ `Activated`. Load any persisted draft in your page's `OnAppearing` as well if you want cold-start restoration.
